*{{cite web |title=Revenge of Shinobi – 2003 Developer Interview |url=http://shmuplations.com/shinobi/ |website=Shmuplations}}</ref> It became America's highest-grossing [[1988 in video games|arcade conversion kit of 1988]],<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Coin Machine: AMOA Jukebox, Games & Cig Vending Awards Winners |magazine=[[Cash Box]] |date=November 26, 1988 |page=30 |url=https://archive.org/details/cashbox52unse_19/page/n29}}</ref> and again one of America's top five highest-grossing [[1989 in video games|conversion kits of 1989]].<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Coin Machine: AMOA Games Awards Nominees Announced |magazine=[[Cash Box]] |date=July 29, 1989 |page=25 |url=https://archive.org/details/cashbox53unse_1/page/25}}</ref>

The arcade game received critical acclaim. Clare Edgeley of ''[[Computer and Video Games]]'' noted it as one of several popular "[[martial arts]] simulation" games at [[London]]'s [[Amusement Trades Exhibition International]] (ATEI) show in January 1988, along with [[Taito]]'s ''[[Ninja Warriors]]'' and [[Data East]]'s ''[[Vigilante (video game)|Vigilante]]''; she said it plays similarly to ''Ninja Warriors'', but that ''Shinobi'' also has elements from [[Namco]]'s [[run and gun video game]] ''[[Rolling Thunder (video game)|Rolling Thunder]]'' (1986), introduces [[bonus stage]]s, and is more challenging overall. She praised the "clean colourful graphics" with large "well defined" sprites, and the action gameplay for being fast-paced and challenging, concluding that the game is "well worth playing".<ref name="CVG77">{{cite magazine |title=Arcade Action |magazine=[[Computer and Video Games]] |date=February 1988 |issue=77 (March 1988) |pages=90–3 |url=https://archive.org/details/cvg-magazine-077/page/n89/mode/2up}}</ref> Nick Kelly of ''[[Commodore User]]'' rated it 8 out of 10, also noting similarities to ''Rolling Thunder'' but said ''Shinobi'' looks good, "plays brilliantly", and "combines several kinds of [[Shoot 'em up|shoot'em]] and [[beat'em up]] action in one well-thought-out, well-executed game."<ref name="CU54">{{cite magazine |title=Arcades: Shinobi |magazine=[[Commodore User]] |date=February 26, 1988 |issue=54 (March 1988) |page=104 |url=https://www.solvalou.com/arcade/reviews/265/307}}</ref> ''[[Sinclair User]]'' also compared it to ''Rolling Thunder'' and other martial arts games, but considers ''Shinobi'' "sufficiently different to be familiar without being boring."<ref name="SU75"/> Retrospectively, ''[[Black Belt (magazine)|Black Belt]]'' magazine in 2003 called ''Shinobi'' "one of the best martial arts arcade games of the 1980s".<ref>{{cite journal |title=Shinobi |journal=[[Black Belt (magazine)|Black Belt]] |date=September 2003 |volume=41 |issue=9 |page=132 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FtwDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT8 |publisher=Active Interest Media, Inc.}}</ref>

Sega's conversion for the Master System received critical acclaim. ''Computer and Video Games'' praised the "well defined" graphics, good sound, and "excellent" gameplay.<ref name="CVG-SMS">{{cite magazine |title=Mean Machines: Shinobi |magazine=[[Computer and Video Games]] |date=September 16, 1988 |issue=84 (October 1988) |page=119 |url=https://archive.org/details/cvg-magazine-084/page/n118}}</ref> It was awarded 4 out of 5 stars in ''[[Dragon (magazine)|Dragon]]''.<ref name="Dragon190">{{cite magazine|last1=Lesser|first1=Hartley|last2=Lesser|first2=Patricia|last3=Lesser|first3=Kirk|name-list-style=amp|date=February 1993|title=The Role of Computers|url=https://archive.org/stream/DragonMagazine260_201801/DragonMagazine190#page/n59/mode/2up|magazine=Dragon|issue=190|pages=55–60}}</ref> [[Classic Game Room]]'s retrospective review reflected that the game is a classic, though less so than the 16-bit sequel ''[[The Revenge of Shinobi (1989 video game)|The Revenge of Shinobi]]''.<ref>{{cite web| title = Classic Game Room HD - Shinobi for Sega Master System| url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K69WhRV19pQ| publisher = Inecom Company| date = November 21, 2008| access-date = April 10, 2013| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140927153041/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K69WhRV19pQ| archive-date = September 27, 2014| url-status = live}}</ref>

